{"type":"simple","docs":[{"id":"/","title":"Commando","description":"Natural-language CLI agent for the Sui ecosystem. One install on Windows, Linux, or macOS - zero config, grounded intelligence.","url":"/","content":"Commando\r\n\r\n One Command. Zero Config. Grounded Intelligence.\r\n\r\nCommando () is a local-first CLI agent that turns plain-English (or Vietnamese!) intent into safe, validated  /  /  commands. It downloads the upstream Mysten Labs binaries for you, bootstraps the wallet and config files you would otherwise hit as paper-cuts on first run, and uses an LLM grounded in live  output to plan each command.\r\n\r\n\r\n  Current release:  — cross-platform (Windows / Linux / macOS), GitHub-direct binary downloads, no secrets shipped in the npm tarball.\r\n\r\n\r\n Why Commando\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n  \r\n  \r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n 60-second tour\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThat's the whole loop. No , no manual , no chasing the right  flags — Commando plans the command, validates it against the live skill contract, and streams the output back.\r\n\r\n How it works\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n1. Router picks the target binary from explicit flags (, , ) or keyword inference.\r\n2. Skill loader trims  (auto-generated from ) to only the relevant tool.\r\n3. LLM planner (OpenAI or OpenRouter) emits structured . The output is parsed defensively and the command path is validated against the allowlist; hallucinated subcommands trigger a retry instead of being executed.\r\n4. Safety gate rejects destructive patterns on every supported OS.\r\n5. Execution engine spawns the real binary, streams stdout/stderr live, and matches the stderr tail against well-known failure patterns to print actionable hints (e.g., \"missing WAL coins → try \").\r\n\r\nRead the full design in Architecture.\r\n\r\n What ships in v0.2.4-beta\r\n\r\n Area  Status \r\n------\r\n Windows x8664  Stable \r\n Linux x8664  Stable \r\n Linux aarch64  Stable (site-builder skipped — no upstream build) \r\n macOS x8664 / arm64  Stable \r\n Auto-bootstrap Sui wallet  Yes () \r\n Auto-bootstrap Walrus config  Yes (, testnet default) \r\n LLM providers  OpenAI, OpenRouter \r\n Mock planner   for offline demos \r\n Secret-free tarball  Yes — operator credentials read from env vars only \r\n\r\n Where to go next"},{"id":"/quickstart","title":"Quickstart","description":"Install Commando, configure an LLM provider, and run your first natural-language Sui command in under 5 minutes.","url":"/quickstart","content":"Quickstart\r\n\r\nBy the end of this page you'll have Commando installed, an LLM provider configured, a Sui testnet wallet, and a successful first prompt — on Windows, Linux, or macOS.\r\n\r\n Prerequisites\r\n\r\n- Node.js 20+ (Node 18 works but is not recommended).\r\n- An OpenAI API key or an OpenRouter API key. (OpenRouter has free tiers — see LLM Setup.)\r\n- 900 MB free disk space for the upstream  /  /  binaries.\r\n\r\n\r\n  Commando is currently published under the  dist-tag. Always install with  until 1.0 ships.\r\n\r\n\r\n 1. Install Commando\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n    \r\n\r\n    The  hook detects your OS + arch, downloads the upstream binaries from GitHub releases into  (or  on Windows), patches your shell PATH, and bootstraps the Sui wallet and Walrus client config.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    For CI / Docker builds where you don't want a 900 MB download during :\r\n\r\n    \r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  Open a new terminal after install so the updated PATH takes effect. On Linux/macOS you may need  or .\r\n\r\n\r\nVerify the install:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n should print your platform, the path to , a green check that the bin folder is on PATH, and  (Unix) or  /  (Windows) for each binary.\r\n\r\n 2. Configure an LLM provider\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis is interactive: pick  or , paste an API key, and choose a model. Defaults are sane ( for OpenAI,  for OpenRouter).\r\n\r\n\r\n  Prefer environment variables? Skip  and just export  or . See LLM Setup for the full picker logic.\r\n\r\n\r\n 3. Get a Sui testnet wallet + gas\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe first command initializes the Sui keystore () if it does not already exist; the faucet prompt hits the public testnet faucet directly so you do not have to remember the URL.\r\n\r\n 4. Run your first real command\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n     Build a Move package\r\n\r\n    From any folder containing a :\r\n\r\n    \r\n\r\n    Commando will plan  (not  — the prompt rules distinguish the verbs explicitly) and stream the compiler output.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n     Deploy to Walrus Sites\r\n\r\n    From a folder containing a built static site (e.g. ):\r\n\r\n    \r\n\r\n    The planner will emit . If you do not yet have WAL or SUI coins on testnet, the runtime hint will tell you exactly which  to run next.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n     Try Walrus directly\r\n\r\n    \r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n 5. Demo / offline mode\r\n\r\nNo internet for the LLM call? Set the mock planner:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nUseful for hackathon demos where the network is unreliable. The mock covers the most common Sui / Walrus / Site-builder verbs.\r\n\r\n CLI summary\r\n\r\n Command  Purpose \r\n------\r\n   Default — plan and execute a natural-language request \r\n   Configure LLM provider, key, and model \r\n   Print environment status and verify binaries \r\n   Re-run the install (download binaries, patch PATH, regen skills) — idempotent \r\n   Regenerate  from the current binaries \r\n   Print the installed version \r\n\r\nRouting flags: , ,  force the target binary and skip the keyword inference step.\r\n\r\n Next steps"},{"id":"/guides/installation","title":"Installation","description":"Cross-platform install details, PATH patching, auto-bootstrapped configs, and the optional R2 mirror.","url":"/guides/installation","content":"Installation\nCommando is shipped as a single npm package, , that runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS. The  hook handles binary downloads, PATH patching, and external CLI config bootstrap.\n Supported platforms\n OS  Arch       \n---------------\n Windows  x8664  Yes  Yes  Yes \n Linux  x8664  Yes  Yes  Yes \n Linux  aarch64  Yes  Yes  Skipped (no upstream build) \n macOS  x8664 (Intel)  Yes  Yes  Yes \n macOS  arm64 (Apple Silicon)  Yes  Yes  Yes \n  On  the upstream  release does not ship a binary, so  is skipped gracefully. Walrus Sites prompts will fail with a clear message; deploy from an x8664 machine instead.\n Install\nThat's it. The hook will:\n1. Detect OS + arch ().\n2. Download  archives directly from the upstream Mysten Labs GitHub releases.\n3. Extract them with the system  and set the executable bit on Unix.\n4. Patch your shell PATH (Windows registry;  /  /  /  on Unix).\n5. Bootstrap the Sui wallet () and Walrus client config (, testnet default).\n6. Generate  from each binary's  output.\n Verify\nExpected output (Linux example):\nIf  is , open a new terminal (or  / ).\n Where things live\n  \n    \n      \n      \n      \n    \n    \n      \n    \n    \n      \n    \n    \n  \n  \n    \n    \n  \n  \n    \n    \n  \n   is required by  for Walrus Sites deploys but is not auto-bootstrapped in 0.2.4-beta. If you hit \"could not find a valid sites configuration file\", download the upstream sample and set . Tracked for auto-bootstrap in a follow-up release.\n Re-running the install\n is idempotent — it skips files that are already present and verified. Use it to:\n- Recover from a partial install (network drop mid-download).\n- Pick up a new binary version after upgrading the npm package.\n- Re-patch PATH after a fresh shell config.\nTo force a full re-download, delete  first.\n Skipping the postinstall (CI / Docker)\nThe 900 MB download is unwelcome in CI pipelines. Skip it with:\nThen run  manually when (and where) you actually need the binaries — e.g., in a separate stage or only on the production runner.\nAny non-empty value other than  or  enables the skip.\n Tuning the downloader\n Env var  Default  Purpose \n---------\n     Parallel downloads. Lower on flaky networks. \n     Per-chunk idle timeout (ms). Increase on slow links. \n     Attempts per file before giving up. \nThe downloader supports HTTP Range resume, so a half-finished  file is reused on the next attempt.\n Optional: R2 manifest mirror (advanced)\nBy default, every install pulls binaries straight from upstream GitHub releases — no operator-owned mirror is involved. For CI mirrors, air-gapped enterprise installs, or future paid tiers we keep an opt-in R2 manifest path that adds per-binary SHA256 provenance.\nEnable it by setting both of these env vars (Windows only — the legacy R2 manifest only ever covered Windows):\nWhen both are present,  fetches the manifest, verifies SHA256 per binary, and installs from there. When either is missing, the install transparently falls back to GitHub-direct.\n  No secrets are shipped inside the npm tarball. If a token previously lived in , it has been removed and rotated. If you are re-using an old worker, generate a fresh secret and update  accordingly.\n Uninstall\nOn Windows, also remove  and the PATH entry that the installer added (the registry edit is reversed on next  if you reinstall later).\n Next"},{"id":"/guides/architecture","title":"Architecture","description":"Components, data flow, the safety model, and the no-secrets-in-tarball posture.","url":"/guides/architecture","content":"Architecture\nCommando is a thin orchestration layer between human intent and three upstream Mysten Labs CLIs. Everything runs locally; nothing in the request path requires a Commando-owned server.\n Component diagram\n 1. Installer & Bootstrap\nTriggered by npm  (also runnable as ). Lives in .\n-  — detects host OS ( /  / ) and arch ( /  / ); throws on unsupported triples with a clear message.\n-  — direct GitHub release downloads; system  extraction; chmod +x on Unix.\n-  +  — opt-in R2 manifest path (Windows only, gated by  + ); adds SHA256 provenance per binary.\n-  — Windows registry edit; appends to  /  /  /  on Unix with an idempotence marker.\n-  — auto-bootstraps  (non-interactive  piped with ) and fetches  from the Mysten docs (testnet default).\n 2. Skill Generator\n shells out to each binary with  (and one level of subcommand ), parses the output into normalized markdown sections, and writes . The generator is platform-aware — it resolves  vs  via  so the same logic works on Windows and Unix.\n is the single source of truth for the LLM planner. Re-run  after upgrading any binary.\n 3. Intent Router\n. Two strategies, in order:\n1. Hard override — , , or  flag wins immediately.\n2. Keyword inference — score-based matching against tool-specific verbs and nouns (e.g. \"publish\", \"move\", \"address\" → sui; \"blob\", \"wal\" → walrus; \"deploy\", \"site\", \"epochs\" → site-builder).\nThe router also performs scope reduction: only the relevant section of  is sent to the LLM, keeping the prompt small and reducing the hallucination surface.\n 4. LLM Planner\n. Calls OpenAI or OpenRouter with a hard-rules system prompt:\n- Output must be a single JSON object .\n- The  value is normalized against an allowlist ( /  / , with the platform-correct  suffix on Windows).\n- Positional arguments (directories, object IDs, hashes) are emitted as bare strings — never as flags.\n- Verbs are disambiguated explicitly ( ≠  ≠ ;  requires the directory).\n Defensive parsing\n extracts the first balanced JSON object from the raw LLM output, even when the model wraps it in prose, markdown fences, or smart quotes. If the model returns nothing usable after the configured retries, the call fails with a clear \"LLM did not return valid JSON\" error.\n Plan validation\n checks:\n1.  is in the allowlist.\n2. The leading non-flag tokens of  form a command path that exists in  (built from ).\n3. Every flag in  exists in the skill contract for that command path.\nA failed check triggers a retry with a tighter hint instead of forwarding a hallucinated command. After the final retry, the call surfaces the validation error.\n Mock mode\n swaps in a deterministic regex-driven planner that covers the most common Sui / Walrus / Site-builder verbs. Useful for hackathon demos with unreliable network and for unit tests.\n 5. Safety Gate\n. Runs twice:\n- Pre-LLM — pattern-matches the raw user prompt against  (cross-platform destructive intent: , , , , , , , ...). Blocks before any tokens are sent to a third party.\n- Post-LLM — pattern-matches the planned  array against . Catches cases where the LLM re-introduces destructive arguments despite a benign-looking prompt.\nPlus the structural allowlist:  must resolve to a file inside .\n 6. Execution Engine\n. Uses  with explicit argument arrays — no shell interpolation, so quoting is never an issue.\n-  — stdin and stdout pass through directly to the user's terminal; stderr is teed to  (live output) and captured into a small ring buffer.\n- On non-zero exit, the ring buffer is matched against . Examples:\n  -  → \"run  to recreate the client config\".\n  -  → \"run  (and verify your context is testnet)\".\n  -  → \"run \".\nThis keeps the user out of \"stare at a stack trace\" mode.\n Data & state\n Path  Owner  Purpose \n---------\n   Commando  Downloaded upstream binaries \n   Commando  Generated command/flag contract for the LLM \n   Commando  Default sandbox profile (configs, keystore, projects) \n   Commando  Temporary downloads, manifests, etc. \n   Sui CLI  Wallet, keystore, client config \n   Walrus CLI  Walrus testnet/mainnet endpoints \n   Site-builder  Walrus Sites contexts (manual in 0.2.4-beta) \nNo server-side user state in MVP.\n Security posture (v0.2.4-beta)\n- No secrets in the npm tarball.  is treated as semi-public; the previous hardcoded R2 manifest auth key was removed and rotated. Operator credentials (R2 token, LLM API keys) are read from env vars only.\n- Local key storage only; no key exfiltration feature.\n- Minimal permission model with local file boundaries.\n- Pre-LLM safety gate keeps destructive intent out of third-party prompts.\n- Post-LLM safety gate + allowlist keeps destructive args off .\n- Optional command audit log (stretch, off by default).\n Reliability choices\n- Direct upstream downloads remove the operator-owned mirror as a single point of failure.\n- Single sandbox profile keeps profile-management bugs out of MVP.\n- Single-step execution per prompt — no multi-step planning loop.\n- Idempotent recovery commands:  and .\n Post-MVP\n- Multiple sandbox profiles + sharing model.\n- Signed command templates and a richer policy engine.\n- Provider routing/fallback for LLM calls.\n- Optional signed manifest distribution (rebuild the R2 path with rotated keys + per-asset signatures).\n Next"},{"id":"/guides/llm-setup","title":"LLM Setup","description":"Pick a provider, set a key, choose a model. Plus the offline mock planner.","url":"/guides/llm-setup","content":"LLM Setup\nCommando uses an LLM to plan each command. You can use OpenAI, OpenRouter, or skip the LLM entirely with the deterministic mock planner.\n Quick decision\n  \n  \n  \n Interactive setup\nThis prompts you for:\n1. Provider —  or .\n2. API key — pasted at the prompt, stored in .\n3. Model — picked from a curated dropdown.\nRe-run  any time to switch providers or models.\n Manual / env-only setup\nIf you'd rather not store the key on disk, set env vars and skip . Commando looks for env vars before falling back to .\n  \n    \n  \n  \n    \n  \nOn Windows PowerShell:\n Curated OpenAI models\nThe  picker keeps the list tight (one screen). Power users can override via .\n ID  Note \n------\n   Flagship, best for complex plans \n   Cheap + fast, good default \n   Next-gen flagship \n   Smaller 4.1 tier \n   Reasoning model \n   Newer reasoning model \nDefault: .\n OpenRouter\nOpenRouter exposes a single OpenAI-compatible endpoint that proxies to dozens of providers. The default model  works without spend, which makes it ideal for first-run testing.\nDefault: .\nOverride with  (e.g. , , ).\n How Commando uses the LLM\nThe planner sends a hard-rules system prompt plus a scoped slice of  (only the section for the routed binary). It expects a single JSON object back:\nOutput is parsed defensively (markdown fences, smart quotes, and surrounding prose are all tolerated). The plan is then validated against the allowlist built from :\n-  must be one of  /  /  (with the platform-correct suffix).\n- The leading non-flag tokens of  must form a real command path.\n- Every flag must exist in the skill contract for that command path.\nA failed validation triggers a retry with a tighter hint instead of executing a hallucinated command.\n  Want to see the full system prompt and validation logic? Read  in the Commando repo.\n Offline / demo mode\nSet  to bypass the LLM entirely:\nThe mock covers:\n- Sui — , , , , , , , .\n- Walrus — , , , basic store/read scaffolding.\n- Site-builder — , , .\nUse it for hackathon demos, CI smoke tests, or to rule out the LLM as a source of bugs while debugging.\n Cost notes\n-  typically costs less than $0.001 per planning call (the prompts are small — usually under 2 KB).\n- OpenRouter free tiers have rate limits; switch to a paid model if you hit them during a demo.\n- The planner makes one LLM call per  invocation under happy path; one extra call per validation retry (max 2 retries by default).\n Next"},{"id":"/guides/safety","title":"Safety","description":"The two-layer safety gate, what it blocks, and how to extend the patterns.","url":"/guides/safety","content":"Safety\nCommando assumes the user is a developer, not an adversary — but it also assumes the LLM occasionally produces nonsense. The safety gate runs twice to keep both human typos and model hallucinations out of .\n The two layers\n Layer 1 — Pre-LLM prompt screen\n matches the raw user input before it reaches a third-party API. Catches things like:\n- , , \n- , , \n- , ,  (fork bomb)\n- , , \n- Prompts attempting to exfiltrate keys (, )\nBlocked prompts never leave your machine.\n Layer 2 — Post-LLM arg screen\n matches the LLM-emitted  array. Catches the case where a benign-looking prompt is misinterpreted into a destructive command, or where a prompt-injection payload smuggled past Layer 1 emerges as an explicit destructive arg.\nBoth layers share most patterns but use different anchoring (free text vs. tokenized argv).\n Structural allowlist\nIndependent of the pattern matchers:\n-  must resolve to a real file inside .\n- The command path (leading non-flag tokens) must be in the allowlist generated from .\n- Every flag must exist in the skill contract for that command path.\nAny failure short-circuits before .\n What you'll see when it fires\nExit code: . No LLM call is made for Layer 1 blocks; no  is made for Layer 2 blocks.\n Extending the patterns\nThe patterns live in :\nTo add a rule:\n1. Add an entry to  and/or  with a clear  (it's surfaced to the user).\n2. Add a unit test in  covering both the positive case (must block) and a negative case (must not over-block).\n3. Run  to make sure existing prompts still plan as before.\n What the gate does not do\n- It does not rate-limit or throttle. If an LLM returns the same wrong plan 100 times, you'll get 100 retries (capped at the validator's max retries).\n- It does not sandbox the spawned process.  and  run with your user's full privileges. Use a dedicated user / container if that matters.\n- It does not scan binary outputs for secrets. Streamed stdout/stderr go to your terminal verbatim.\n- It does not parse Move source code for malicious constructs. The gate is at the CLI layer, not the application layer.\n Disabling (don't)\nThere is no kill switch for the safety gate in 0.2.4-beta — the worst case is a noisy false positive that you can route around by running the underlying CLI directly. If you have a legitimate reason for a  mode, file an issue with your use case.\n Related"},{"id":"/guides/troubleshooting","title":"Troubleshooting","description":"Common errors, what they mean, and the runtime hints Commando prints for them.","url":"/guides/troubleshooting","content":"Troubleshooting\nCommando tries to fail loudly with a hint, not silently with a stack trace. Each entry below shows the error you see, the root cause, and the fix.\n Install / bootstrap\n  after install\nCause: Your shell session was started before the installer patched  /  / Windows registry.\nFix: Open a new terminal. On Linux/macOS you can also  (or ).\n---\n \nCause: The  step failed silently, or the global npm bin directory is not on your PATH.\nFix:\n---\n \nCause: Network drop, firewall, or upstream GitHub release URL changed.\nFix:  is idempotent and supports HTTP Range resume, so re-running it is cheap:\nIf the URL changed (rare; we pin tags), you'll need a Commando upgrade: .\n---\n  on Linux ARM\nCause: Upstream  does not ship a  build. Commando skips it on purpose.\nFix: Run Walrus Sites prompts on an x8664 machine. Other Walrus operations (info, store, read) work fine on ARM.\n Sui\n \nCause: Wallet has less testnet SUI than the operation requires (typically ≥ 0.5 SUI for ).\nFix:\nIf the faucet times out, wait 5-10s and retry; the public testnet faucet is rate-limited per address.\n---\n \nCause: A pre-0.2.3-beta build hard-coded  on Linux. Upgrade.\nFix:\n---\n  runs \nCause: Pre-0.2.3-beta planner conflated build/test/publish.\nFix: Upgrade to 0.2.4-beta — the system prompt now disambiguates the verbs explicitly and the validator rejects the wrong path.\n Walrus\n \nCause:  is missing. Either bootstrap was skipped () or the auto-fetch failed.\nFix:\n---\n \nCause: Either you have no WAL coins, or your Walrus context is  but your coins are on  (or vice versa).\nFix:\nThe runtime hint that prints this error includes the same checklist.\n Site-builder\n \nCause:  is missing. Not auto-bootstrapped in 0.2.4-beta (tracked for a follow-up).\nFix:\n---\n  from \nCause: The LLM omitted the positional directory argument.\nFix: Be explicit in the prompt:\nThe 0.2.4-beta system prompt includes hardened rules for positional arguments; if you see this in 0.2.4+, file an issue with the exact prompt.\n LLM / planner\n \nCause: The model produced prose-only output and the defensive parser couldn't extract a JSON object after the configured retries.\nFix:\n1. Try a stronger model: .\n2. Re-phrase the prompt more concretely (verbs + objects, no rhetorical questions).\n3. Use the offline mock for known intents: .\n---\n \nCause: The model hallucinated a subcommand that doesn't exist in the current  CLI.\nFix: This is the validator working as intended — the planner will retry with a tighter hint. If it persists across retries:\n Safety gate\n \nCause: Your prompt matched a  rule (Layer 1) — destructive intent, key exfiltration attempt, etc.\nFix: Read the printed . If you genuinely need to do that destructive operation, run the underlying command directly — Commando doesn't execute prompts that look like system-wipe requests.\nFalse positive? File an issue with the exact prompt and the matched rule name; we'll narrow the regex.\n Diagnostics\nWhen in doubt:\nThis prints:\n- Node version and platform.\n-  path and PATH membership.\n- Per-binary status ( /  /  / ).\n- LLM provider, model, and whether the key is configured.\n-  setting.\nAttach the full  output when filing an issue.\n Still stuck?"},{"id":"/examples/sui-flows","title":"Sui Cookbook","description":"Copy-paste prompts for the most common Sui flows - wallet, faucet, gas, build, publish.","url":"/examples/sui-flows","content":"Sui Cookbook\nEvery prompt below has been validated against the 0.2.4-beta planner and the current  CLI. Run them as-is.\n Wallet\n Create a new address\nPlans . The first run also bootstraps  if it doesn't already exist.\n Show the active address\nPlans . Use the  flag for predictability.\n Show the active environment\nPlans . Useful before publishing — confirm you're on , not .\n Switch environment\nPlans  (or ).\n Gas\n Check gas\nPlans . Each row is a coin object you can spend.\n Get testnet SUI from the faucet\nCommando hits the public testnet faucet directly via HTTP for the active address; you don't need to remember the URL or paste the address yourself. Wait 5-10 seconds, then re-run  to confirm.\n  The faucet is rate-limited per address. If you get throttled, wait 60s and retry.\n Move\nAll Move prompts run from a folder containing a . The 0.2.4-beta planner explicitly disambiguates build vs test vs publish — three different verbs, three different commands.\n Build\nPlans . Does not publish.\n Test\nPlans . Streams the test runner output directly.\n Publish\nPlans  (or similar). Make sure you have:\n1. ≥ 0.1 SUI in gas ().\n2. Successfully built ().\n3. Active env is  ( if not).\nThe published package ID is in the transaction effects — Commando streams them verbatim.\n Putting it together\nA clean \"fresh machine to deployed contract\" sequence on Linux/macOS:\n  \n     Install + LLM key\n    \n  \n  \n     Wallet + gas\n    \n  \n  \n     Build + publish\n    \n  \nTotal wall time on a clean machine: 5 minutes (mostly the binary download in step 1).\n Common issues\n Symptom  See \n------\n   Troubleshooting → Sui \n  runs   Upgrade to ≥ 0.2.4-beta \n  for  on Linux  Upgrade to ≥ 0.2.3-beta \n Related"},{"id":"/examples/walrus-sites","title":"Walrus Sites — End to End","description":"Deploy a static site to Walrus Sites with one cmdo prompt, including the testnet wallet and WAL/SUI funding steps.","url":"/examples/walrus-sites","content":"Walrus Sites — End to End\nThis walkthrough takes you from a freshly built static site () to a live Walrus Sites URL using only  prompts. Tested on Ubuntu x8664 with Commando 0.2.4-beta.\n  Walrus Sites requires , which is not available on . Use Windows, Linux x8664, or macOS.\n Prerequisites\n- Commando ≥ 0.2.4-beta installed and  is green.\n- A built static site folder (e.g.  from ). 1 MB is plenty for a first deploy.\n- An LLM provider configured (), or  for offline mode.\n 1. Wallet + gas\nYou need a Sui testnet wallet with ≥ 0.5 SUI. If you already have one, skip ahead.\nConfirm at least one coin with balance ≥  MIST (= 0.5 SUI). Re-run the faucet prompt if needed.\n 2. WAL coins\nWalrus Sites pays for blob storage in WAL. Fetch some testnet WAL:\nThis plans , which uses your active SUI to mint testnet WAL via the WAL exchange. Run twice if your first deploy is large (10 MB site needs more WAL than a 1 MB site).\n  If you see  during the deploy step, your Walrus context is probably set to  while your WAL is on . See the WAL coin troubleshooting entry.\n 3. Sites config\n requires . Not auto-bootstrapped in 0.2.4-beta:\nVerify:\n 4. Deploy\nFrom the folder containing your built site:\nThe planner emits something like . Commando spawns it, streams progress, and prints the resulting site object ID and URL on success.\nEquivalent explicit prompt if you want to control the epoch count:\n controls how many storage epochs the site is paid for upfront. 1 epoch ≈ 24 hours on testnet at the time of writing.\n 5. Verify\nThe deploy output includes a Sui object ID for your site (e.g. ). Browse it:\n- Walrus Sites portal: \n- Inspect via site-builder:\n  \n  Plans .\n 6. Update later\nTo push a new version of the site to the same object ID:\nPlans . Same WAL/SUI cost rules apply.\n End-to-end timing\nOn a clean Ubuntu VPS (Commando 0.2.4-beta, 860 KB site):\n Step  Wall time \n------\n Install + bootstrap  3 min (binary download) \n Wallet + faucet  30 s \n   30 s \n  (1 epoch, 1 MB)  60 s \n Total  5 min \n Troubleshooting checklist\n Error  Fix \n------\n   Run the curl command in step 3. \n   Check both  and  are on , then . \n   , wait, retry. \n   Be explicit: . \n  on   You're on . Deploy from x8664 instead. \nFull table: Troubleshooting.\n Related"},{"id":"/reference/cli","title":"CLI Reference","description":"Every cmdo subcommand and flag in v0.2.4-beta.","url":"/reference/cli","content":"CLI Reference\n is a Commander-based CLI. The default action takes a free-text prompt; the rest are reserved subcommand names.\n Synopsis\n Global options\n Option  Description \n------\n ,   Print the installed version (e.g. ). \n ,   Print help. \n Subcommands\n \nInteractively configure the LLM provider, API key, and model.\nPrompts:\n1. Provider —  or .\n2. API key — pasted at the prompt; stored in .\n3. Model — picked from a curated dropdown (or accept the default).\nRe-run any time to switch providers or models. Env vars (, , , ) override the stored config when present.\n \nPrint environment status and verify installed binaries. Read-only — does not download or modify anything.\nOutput includes Node version, platform, install root, PATH membership, per-binary status, and LLM provider configuration. See Troubleshooting for what to do when checks fail.\nExit code:  if all checks pass,  otherwise.\n \nDownload binaries, patch PATH, bootstrap external CLI configs, and (re)generate skills. Idempotent — safe to re-run.\nUse this after a partial install (network drop), after upgrading the package, or to recover from a stale state. To force a full re-download, delete  first.\n \nRegenerate  from the currently installed binaries'  output.\nRun this after any of the upstream binaries change versions — the LLM planner is constrained to the contract in , so a stale contract means stale plans.\n \nThe default action. Anything that isn't a known subcommand is treated as a natural-language prompt.\n Routing flags\nIf multiple are passed, the first one wins.\n Flag  Forces \n------\n   Plan against the  binary skill section only. \n   Plan against the  binary skill section only. \n   Plan against the  binary skill section only. \nWhen no flag is passed, the router infers the target from prompt keywords. Always pass the explicit flag in scripts and demos for predictability.\n Exit codes\n Code  Meaning \n------\n   Plan succeeded, executed, and exited 0. \n   Generic failure (LLM error, validation failure, spawn failure, exec non-zero). \n   Underlying binary's exit code is propagated. \n Examples\n Wallet\n Move\n Walrus\n Walrus Sites\n Where the binary lives\n OS  Path \n------\n Windows   (npm global bin) →  for upstream binaries \n Linux / macOS   →  for upstream binaries \n Related"},{"id":"/reference/env-vars","title":"Environment Variables","description":"Every CMDO_*, OPENAI_*, OPENROUTER_* variable Commando reads, with defaults.","url":"/reference/env-vars","content":"Environment Variables\nAll variables are read at process start. There is no live reload — change the env, then re-run .\n Installer\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Any non-empty value other than  /  skips the postinstall download. Use  later. \n     Parallel downloads during bootstrap. Lower on flaky networks. \n     Per-chunk idle timeout in milliseconds. Increase for slow links. \n     Attempts per file before giving up. \n Optional R2 manifest mirror (Windows only)\nThe R2 path is off by default. Set both vars to enable. When either is missing, the install falls back to GitHub-direct.\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Full URL to the manifest JSON in R2 (or any compatible mirror). \n   unset  Bearer/header token the worker accepts. \n  No secret is shipped inside the npm tarball — both halves must come from the operator's environment. See Installation for the security rationale.\n LLM provider\nEnv vars override the values stored by  in .\n OpenAI\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Required if provider is OpenAI and no config file exists. \n     Override the model. Any string accepted by the OpenAI API. \n OpenRouter\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Required if provider is OpenRouter and no config file exists. \n     Override the model. Any string accepted by OpenRouter. \n Planner\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n     Set to  to bypass the LLM and use the deterministic regex-based mock planner. Useful for offline demos and CI. \n Logging\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n     One of , , , .  adds raw LLM input/output and validator decisions. \n   unset  Standard env: any non-empty value disables ANSI colors. \n Examples\n CI build that defers the binary download\n Air-gapped install pulling from a private R2 mirror\n Prefer env-only LLM setup (no )\n Offline hackathon demo\n Related"},{"id":"/examples\\sui-flows","title":"Sui Cookbook","description":"Copy-paste prompts for the most common Sui flows - wallet, faucet, gas, build, publish.","url":"/examples\\sui-flows","content":"Sui Cookbook\nEvery prompt below has been validated against the 0.2.4-beta planner and the current  CLI. Run them as-is.\n Wallet\n Create a new address\nPlans . The first run also bootstraps  if it doesn't already exist.\n Show the active address\nPlans . Use the  flag for predictability.\n Show the active environment\nPlans . Useful before publishing — confirm you're on , not .\n Switch environment\nPlans  (or ).\n Gas\n Check gas\nPlans . Each row is a coin object you can spend.\n Get testnet SUI from the faucet\nCommando hits the public testnet faucet directly via HTTP for the active address; you don't need to remember the URL or paste the address yourself. Wait 5-10 seconds, then re-run  to confirm.\n  The faucet is rate-limited per address. If you get throttled, wait 60s and retry.\n Move\nAll Move prompts run from a folder containing a . The 0.2.4-beta planner explicitly disambiguates build vs test vs publish — three different verbs, three different commands.\n Build\nPlans . Does not publish.\n Test\nPlans . Streams the test runner output directly.\n Publish\nPlans  (or similar). Make sure you have:\n1. ≥ 0.1 SUI in gas ().\n2. Successfully built ().\n3. Active env is  ( if not).\nThe published package ID is in the transaction effects — Commando streams them verbatim.\n Putting it together\nA clean \"fresh machine to deployed contract\" sequence on Linux/macOS:\n  \n     Install + LLM key\n    \n  \n  \n     Wallet + gas\n    \n  \n  \n     Build + publish\n    \n  \nTotal wall time on a clean machine: 5 minutes (mostly the binary download in step 1).\n Common issues\n Symptom  See \n------\n   Troubleshooting → Sui \n  runs   Upgrade to ≥ 0.2.4-beta \n  for  on Linux  Upgrade to ≥ 0.2.3-beta \n Related"},{"id":"/examples\\walrus-sites","title":"Walrus Sites — End to End","description":"Deploy a static site to Walrus Sites with one cmdo prompt, including the testnet wallet and WAL/SUI funding steps.","url":"/examples\\walrus-sites","content":"Walrus Sites — End to End\nThis walkthrough takes you from a freshly built static site () to a live Walrus Sites URL using only  prompts. Tested on Ubuntu x8664 with Commando 0.2.4-beta.\n  Walrus Sites requires , which is not available on . Use Windows, Linux x8664, or macOS.\n Prerequisites\n- Commando ≥ 0.2.4-beta installed and  is green.\n- A built static site folder (e.g.  from ). 1 MB is plenty for a first deploy.\n- An LLM provider configured (), or  for offline mode.\n 1. Wallet + gas\nYou need a Sui testnet wallet with ≥ 0.5 SUI. If you already have one, skip ahead.\nConfirm at least one coin with balance ≥  MIST (= 0.5 SUI). Re-run the faucet prompt if needed.\n 2. WAL coins\nWalrus Sites pays for blob storage in WAL. Fetch some testnet WAL:\nThis plans , which uses your active SUI to mint testnet WAL via the WAL exchange. Run twice if your first deploy is large (10 MB site needs more WAL than a 1 MB site).\n  If you see  during the deploy step, your Walrus context is probably set to  while your WAL is on . See the WAL coin troubleshooting entry.\n 3. Sites config\n requires . Not auto-bootstrapped in 0.2.4-beta:\nVerify:\n 4. Deploy\nFrom the folder containing your built site:\nThe planner emits something like . Commando spawns it, streams progress, and prints the resulting site object ID and URL on success.\nEquivalent explicit prompt if you want to control the epoch count:\n controls how many storage epochs the site is paid for upfront. 1 epoch ≈ 24 hours on testnet at the time of writing.\n 5. Verify\nThe deploy output includes a Sui object ID for your site (e.g. ). Browse it:\n- Walrus Sites portal: \n- Inspect via site-builder:\n  \n  Plans .\n 6. Update later\nTo push a new version of the site to the same object ID:\nPlans . Same WAL/SUI cost rules apply.\n End-to-end timing\nOn a clean Ubuntu VPS (Commando 0.2.4-beta, 860 KB site):\n Step  Wall time \n------\n Install + bootstrap  3 min (binary download) \n Wallet + faucet  30 s \n   30 s \n  (1 epoch, 1 MB)  60 s \n Total  5 min \n Troubleshooting checklist\n Error  Fix \n------\n   Run the curl command in step 3. \n   Check both  and  are on , then . \n   , wait, retry. \n   Be explicit: . \n  on   You're on . Deploy from x8664 instead. \nFull table: Troubleshooting.\n Related"},{"id":"/guides\\architecture","title":"Architecture","description":"Components, data flow, the safety model, and the no-secrets-in-tarball posture.","url":"/guides\\architecture","content":"Architecture\nCommando is a thin orchestration layer between human intent and three upstream Mysten Labs CLIs. Everything runs locally; nothing in the request path requires a Commando-owned server.\n Component diagram\n 1. Installer & Bootstrap\nTriggered by npm  (also runnable as ). Lives in .\n-  — detects host OS ( /  / ) and arch ( /  / ); throws on unsupported triples with a clear message.\n-  — direct GitHub release downloads; system  extraction; chmod +x on Unix.\n-  +  — opt-in R2 manifest path (Windows only, gated by  + ); adds SHA256 provenance per binary.\n-  — Windows registry edit; appends to  /  /  /  on Unix with an idempotence marker.\n-  — auto-bootstraps  (non-interactive  piped with ) and fetches  from the Mysten docs (testnet default).\n 2. Skill Generator\n shells out to each binary with  (and one level of subcommand ), parses the output into normalized markdown sections, and writes . The generator is platform-aware — it resolves  vs  via  so the same logic works on Windows and Unix.\n is the single source of truth for the LLM planner. Re-run  after upgrading any binary.\n 3. Intent Router\n. Two strategies, in order:\n1. Hard override — , , or  flag wins immediately.\n2. Keyword inference — score-based matching against tool-specific verbs and nouns (e.g. \"publish\", \"move\", \"address\" → sui; \"blob\", \"wal\" → walrus; \"deploy\", \"site\", \"epochs\" → site-builder).\nThe router also performs scope reduction: only the relevant section of  is sent to the LLM, keeping the prompt small and reducing the hallucination surface.\n 4. LLM Planner\n. Calls OpenAI or OpenRouter with a hard-rules system prompt:\n- Output must be a single JSON object .\n- The  value is normalized against an allowlist ( /  / , with the platform-correct  suffix on Windows).\n- Positional arguments (directories, object IDs, hashes) are emitted as bare strings — never as flags.\n- Verbs are disambiguated explicitly ( ≠  ≠ ;  requires the directory).\n Defensive parsing\n extracts the first balanced JSON object from the raw LLM output, even when the model wraps it in prose, markdown fences, or smart quotes. If the model returns nothing usable after the configured retries, the call fails with a clear \"LLM did not return valid JSON\" error.\n Plan validation\n checks:\n1.  is in the allowlist.\n2. The leading non-flag tokens of  form a command path that exists in  (built from ).\n3. Every flag in  exists in the skill contract for that command path.\nA failed check triggers a retry with a tighter hint instead of forwarding a hallucinated command. After the final retry, the call surfaces the validation error.\n Mock mode\n swaps in a deterministic regex-driven planner that covers the most common Sui / Walrus / Site-builder verbs. Useful for hackathon demos with unreliable network and for unit tests.\n 5. Safety Gate\n. Runs twice:\n- Pre-LLM — pattern-matches the raw user prompt against  (cross-platform destructive intent: , , , , , , , ...). Blocks before any tokens are sent to a third party.\n- Post-LLM — pattern-matches the planned  array against . Catches cases where the LLM re-introduces destructive arguments despite a benign-looking prompt.\nPlus the structural allowlist:  must resolve to a file inside .\n 6. Execution Engine\n. Uses  with explicit argument arrays — no shell interpolation, so quoting is never an issue.\n-  — stdin and stdout pass through directly to the user's terminal; stderr is teed to  (live output) and captured into a small ring buffer.\n- On non-zero exit, the ring buffer is matched against . Examples:\n  -  → \"run  to recreate the client config\".\n  -  → \"run  (and verify your context is testnet)\".\n  -  → \"run \".\nThis keeps the user out of \"stare at a stack trace\" mode.\n Data & state\n Path  Owner  Purpose \n---------\n   Commando  Downloaded upstream binaries \n   Commando  Generated command/flag contract for the LLM \n   Commando  Default sandbox profile (configs, keystore, projects) \n   Commando  Temporary downloads, manifests, etc. \n   Sui CLI  Wallet, keystore, client config \n   Walrus CLI  Walrus testnet/mainnet endpoints \n   Site-builder  Walrus Sites contexts (manual in 0.2.4-beta) \nNo server-side user state in MVP.\n Security posture (v0.2.4-beta)\n- No secrets in the npm tarball.  is treated as semi-public; the previous hardcoded R2 manifest auth key was removed and rotated. Operator credentials (R2 token, LLM API keys) are read from env vars only.\n- Local key storage only; no key exfiltration feature.\n- Minimal permission model with local file boundaries.\n- Pre-LLM safety gate keeps destructive intent out of third-party prompts.\n- Post-LLM safety gate + allowlist keeps destructive args off .\n- Optional command audit log (stretch, off by default).\n Reliability choices\n- Direct upstream downloads remove the operator-owned mirror as a single point of failure.\n- Single sandbox profile keeps profile-management bugs out of MVP.\n- Single-step execution per prompt — no multi-step planning loop.\n- Idempotent recovery commands:  and .\n Post-MVP\n- Multiple sandbox profiles + sharing model.\n- Signed command templates and a richer policy engine.\n- Provider routing/fallback for LLM calls.\n- Optional signed manifest distribution (rebuild the R2 path with rotated keys + per-asset signatures).\n Next"},{"id":"/guides\\components","title":"Components","description":"Every built-in UI component, with examples you can copy.","url":"/guides\\components","content":"Components\r\n\r\ncmdocs ships with a rich set of components. Use them in any MDX file — no imports required.\r\n\r\n Callout\r\n\r\nHighlight important information.\r\n\r\n\r\n  This is an informational callout. Use it for tips and notes.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  This is a warning callout. Use it for caveats and gotchas.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  This is an error callout. Use it for destructive actions or critical warnings.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Cards\r\n\r\nDisplay linked content in a responsive grid.\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe  prop accepts any Lucide icon name.\r\n\r\n Tabs\r\n\r\nSwitch between content views.\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n    \r\n  \r\n  \r\n    \r\n  \r\n  \r\n    \r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\nbash\r\n    npm install cmdocs\r\n    bash\r\n    bun add cmdocs\r\n    bash\r\n    pnpm add cmdocs\r\n    cmdocs init.cmdocs.app\r\n\r\nMermaid diagrams adapt to light and dark themes automatically.\r\n\r\n Images\r\n\r\nAll images are zoomable — click to expand. Use either Markdown or :\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPlace images in the  folder and reference them with an absolute path starting with .\r\n\r\n Banner\r\n\r\nDisplay a site-wide announcement above the navbar. Use  at the top of any MDX file — the most recent occurrence wins, and it appears on every page:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBanners support full Markdown, including links and inline code. Common patterns:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTo remove the banner, delete the  tag from your MDX. To show it only on certain pages, place the tag only in those files.\r\n\r\n Component reference"},{"id":"/guides\\deploy","title":"Deploy","description":"Ship your documentation with the cmdocs dashboard — push to deploy.","url":"/guides\\deploy","content":"Deploy\r\n\r\ncmdocs is push-to-deploy. Connect your GitHub repo in the cmdocs dashboard, and every commit to your tracked branch produces a new build and deploys automatically. No CLI export, no manual uploads, no hosting config to maintain.\r\n\r\n What you get\r\n\r\n Feature  Description \r\n------\r\n Git integration  One-click GitHub OAuth + repo picker; webhooks configured for you \r\n Auto-builds on push  Every commit to your tracked branch produces a fresh deployment \r\n Multiple environments  Production, staging, and preview branches — each tracking its own branch \r\n Subdomain + HTTPS  Each environment gets  with TLS provisioned automatically \r\n Custom domains  Bring your own domain — DNS instructions in project settings \r\n Build logs  Live, streaming logs per build; errors surface inline \r\n Deployment history  Roll back to any previous deployment in one click \r\n\r\n How it works\r\n\r\nGH: git push main\r\n    GH-API: webhook (HMAC verified)\r\n    API-API: create deployment (queued)\r\n    API-W: enqueue build job\r\n    W-GH: clone repo\r\n    W-W: run cmdocs pipeline\r\n    W-W: static export (HTML + CSS + JS)\r\n    W-API: upload artifacts\r\n    API-CDN: publish\r\n    CDN--Dev: site live at subdomain\" /\r\n\r\nA typical build finishes in under a minute.\r\n\r\n Walkthrough\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n     Sign in\r\n\r\n    Go to cmdocs.sh and sign in with GitHub.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n     Install the cmdocs GitHub App\r\n\r\n    The dashboard prompts you to install the cmdocs GitHub App. Grant it access to the repos you want to deploy — you can pick a single repo or your whole org.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n     Create a project\r\n\r\n    Click New project, select your docs repository, and confirm the default branch (usually ).\r\n  \r\n  \r\n     Watch the first build\r\n\r\n    The first build starts automatically. Watch the logs stream live in the dashboard. When the build turns green, your site is reachable at .\r\n  \r\n  \r\n     Push to deploy\r\n\r\n    Every subsequent commit to the tracked branch triggers a new build. Roll back to any previous version from the Deployments tab.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  Before you push, run  locally — it runs the same validation the build worker does and catches typos, missing pages, and broken links before they consume CI minutes. See the Validate guide to wire it into a pre-commit hook.\r\n\r\n\r\n Environments\r\n\r\nEvery project starts with a production environment tracking . Add more environments for staging or feature branches:\r\n\r\n Environment  Branch  Subdomain  Triggers on \r\n------------\r\n       Push to  \r\n       Push to  \r\n   any PR    PR opened/updated \r\n\r\nConfigure them under Project → Settings → Environments.\r\n\r\n Custom domains\r\n\r\nAdd your own domain under Project → Settings → Domains. The dashboard walks you through the DNS records to add at your registrar and provisions TLS via Let's Encrypt automatically once DNS propagates.\r\n\r\n Troubleshooting\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n    Run  locally — it will surface the exact schema problem before you push. The build worker runs the same validation; if it fails, the error message in the dashboard is the same you'll see locally.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    Assets must live under  in your repo. A path like  is served at . If an asset is missing,  catches it for files referenced in ; assets referenced only from MDX still need to be under .\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    In project settings, set the Source directory to the path of your  (for example,  or ). The dashboard only rebuilds when files inside that directory change.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    Yes — add a new environment tracking that branch. Or enable PR previews: every open PR gets its own  deployment that updates on each push.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    Open the Deployments tab, find the last known-good deployment, and click Promote. It's instant — no rebuild.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n Next steps"},{"id":"/guides\\installation","title":"Installation","description":"Cross-platform install details, PATH patching, auto-bootstrapped configs, and the optional R2 mirror.","url":"/guides\\installation","content":"Installation\nCommando is shipped as a single npm package, , that runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS. The  hook handles binary downloads, PATH patching, and external CLI config bootstrap.\n Supported platforms\n OS  Arch       \n---------------\n Windows  x8664  Yes  Yes  Yes \n Linux  x8664  Yes  Yes  Yes \n Linux  aarch64  Yes  Yes  Skipped (no upstream build) \n macOS  x8664 (Intel)  Yes  Yes  Yes \n macOS  arm64 (Apple Silicon)  Yes  Yes  Yes \n  On  the upstream  release does not ship a binary, so  is skipped gracefully. Walrus Sites prompts will fail with a clear message; deploy from an x8664 machine instead.\n Install\nThat's it. The hook will:\n1. Detect OS + arch ().\n2. Download  archives directly from the upstream Mysten Labs GitHub releases.\n3. Extract them with the system  and set the executable bit on Unix.\n4. Patch your shell PATH (Windows registry;  /  /  /  on Unix).\n5. Bootstrap the Sui wallet () and Walrus client config (, testnet default).\n6. Generate  from each binary's  output.\n Verify\nExpected output (Linux example):\nIf  is , open a new terminal (or  / ).\n Where things live\n  \n    \n      \n      \n      \n    \n    \n      \n    \n    \n      \n    \n    \n  \n  \n    \n    \n  \n  \n    \n    \n  \n   is required by  for Walrus Sites deploys but is not auto-bootstrapped in 0.2.4-beta. If you hit \"could not find a valid sites configuration file\", download the upstream sample and set . Tracked for auto-bootstrap in a follow-up release.\n Re-running the install\n is idempotent — it skips files that are already present and verified. Use it to:\n- Recover from a partial install (network drop mid-download).\n- Pick up a new binary version after upgrading the npm package.\n- Re-patch PATH after a fresh shell config.\nTo force a full re-download, delete  first.\n Skipping the postinstall (CI / Docker)\nThe 900 MB download is unwelcome in CI pipelines. Skip it with:\nThen run  manually when (and where) you actually need the binaries — e.g., in a separate stage or only on the production runner.\nAny non-empty value other than  or  enables the skip.\n Tuning the downloader\n Env var  Default  Purpose \n---------\n     Parallel downloads. Lower on flaky networks. \n     Per-chunk idle timeout (ms). Increase on slow links. \n     Attempts per file before giving up. \nThe downloader supports HTTP Range resume, so a half-finished  file is reused on the next attempt.\n Optional: R2 manifest mirror (advanced)\nBy default, every install pulls binaries straight from upstream GitHub releases — no operator-owned mirror is involved. For CI mirrors, air-gapped enterprise installs, or future paid tiers we keep an opt-in R2 manifest path that adds per-binary SHA256 provenance.\nEnable it by setting both of these env vars (Windows only — the legacy R2 manifest only ever covered Windows):\nWhen both are present,  fetches the manifest, verifies SHA256 per binary, and installs from there. When either is missing, the install transparently falls back to GitHub-direct.\n  No secrets are shipped inside the npm tarball. If a token previously lived in , it has been removed and rotated. If you are re-using an old worker, generate a fresh secret and update  accordingly.\n Uninstall\nOn Windows, also remove  and the PATH entry that the installer added (the registry edit is reversed on next  if you reinstall later).\n Next"},{"id":"/guides\\llm-setup","title":"LLM Setup","description":"Pick a provider, set a key, choose a model. Plus the offline mock planner.","url":"/guides\\llm-setup","content":"LLM Setup\nCommando uses an LLM to plan each command. You can use OpenAI, OpenRouter, or skip the LLM entirely with the deterministic mock planner.\n Quick decision\n  \n  \n  \n Interactive setup\nThis prompts you for:\n1. Provider —  or .\n2. API key — pasted at the prompt, stored in .\n3. Model — picked from a curated dropdown.\nRe-run  any time to switch providers or models.\n Manual / env-only setup\nIf you'd rather not store the key on disk, set env vars and skip . Commando looks for env vars before falling back to .\n  \n    \n  \n  \n    \n  \nOn Windows PowerShell:\n Curated OpenAI models\nThe  picker keeps the list tight (one screen). Power users can override via .\n ID  Note \n------\n   Flagship, best for complex plans \n   Cheap + fast, good default \n   Next-gen flagship \n   Smaller 4.1 tier \n   Reasoning model \n   Newer reasoning model \nDefault: .\n OpenRouter\nOpenRouter exposes a single OpenAI-compatible endpoint that proxies to dozens of providers. The default model  works without spend, which makes it ideal for first-run testing.\nDefault: .\nOverride with  (e.g. , , ).\n How Commando uses the LLM\nThe planner sends a hard-rules system prompt plus a scoped slice of  (only the section for the routed binary). It expects a single JSON object back:\nOutput is parsed defensively (markdown fences, smart quotes, and surrounding prose are all tolerated). The plan is then validated against the allowlist built from :\n-  must be one of  /  /  (with the platform-correct suffix).\n- The leading non-flag tokens of  must form a real command path.\n- Every flag must exist in the skill contract for that command path.\nA failed validation triggers a retry with a tighter hint instead of executing a hallucinated command.\n  Want to see the full system prompt and validation logic? Read  in the Commando repo.\n Offline / demo mode\nSet  to bypass the LLM entirely:\nThe mock covers:\n- Sui — , , , , , , , .\n- Walrus — , , , basic store/read scaffolding.\n- Site-builder — , , .\nUse it for hackathon demos, CI smoke tests, or to rule out the LLM as a source of bugs while debugging.\n Cost notes\n-  typically costs less than $0.001 per planning call (the prompts are small — usually under 2 KB).\n- OpenRouter free tiers have rate limits; switch to a paid model if you hit them during a demo.\n- The planner makes one LLM call per  invocation under happy path; one extra call per validation retry (max 2 retries by default).\n Next"},{"id":"/guides\\safety","title":"Safety","description":"The two-layer safety gate, what it blocks, and how to extend the patterns.","url":"/guides\\safety","content":"Safety\nCommando assumes the user is a developer, not an adversary — but it also assumes the LLM occasionally produces nonsense. The safety gate runs twice to keep both human typos and model hallucinations out of .\n The two layers\n Layer 1 — Pre-LLM prompt screen\n matches the raw user input before it reaches a third-party API. Catches things like:\n- , , \n- , , \n- , ,  (fork bomb)\n- , , \n- Prompts attempting to exfiltrate keys (, )\nBlocked prompts never leave your machine.\n Layer 2 — Post-LLM arg screen\n matches the LLM-emitted  array. Catches the case where a benign-looking prompt is misinterpreted into a destructive command, or where a prompt-injection payload smuggled past Layer 1 emerges as an explicit destructive arg.\nBoth layers share most patterns but use different anchoring (free text vs. tokenized argv).\n Structural allowlist\nIndependent of the pattern matchers:\n-  must resolve to a real file inside .\n- The command path (leading non-flag tokens) must be in the allowlist generated from .\n- Every flag must exist in the skill contract for that command path.\nAny failure short-circuits before .\n What you'll see when it fires\nExit code: . No LLM call is made for Layer 1 blocks; no  is made for Layer 2 blocks.\n Extending the patterns\nThe patterns live in :\nTo add a rule:\n1. Add an entry to  and/or  with a clear  (it's surfaced to the user).\n2. Add a unit test in  covering both the positive case (must block) and a negative case (must not over-block).\n3. Run  to make sure existing prompts still plan as before.\n What the gate does not do\n- It does not rate-limit or throttle. If an LLM returns the same wrong plan 100 times, you'll get 100 retries (capped at the validator's max retries).\n- It does not sandbox the spawned process.  and  run with your user's full privileges. Use a dedicated user / container if that matters.\n- It does not scan binary outputs for secrets. Streamed stdout/stderr go to your terminal verbatim.\n- It does not parse Move source code for malicious constructs. The gate is at the CLI layer, not the application layer.\n Disabling (don't)\nThere is no kill switch for the safety gate in 0.2.4-beta — the worst case is a noisy false positive that you can route around by running the underlying CLI directly. If you have a legitimate reason for a  mode, file an issue with your use case.\n Related"},{"id":"/guides\\troubleshooting","title":"Troubleshooting","description":"Common errors, what they mean, and the runtime hints Commando prints for them.","url":"/guides\\troubleshooting","content":"Troubleshooting\nCommando tries to fail loudly with a hint, not silently with a stack trace. Each entry below shows the error you see, the root cause, and the fix.\n Install / bootstrap\n  after install\nCause: Your shell session was started before the installer patched  /  / Windows registry.\nFix: Open a new terminal. On Linux/macOS you can also  (or ).\n---\n \nCause: The  step failed silently, or the global npm bin directory is not on your PATH.\nFix:\n---\n \nCause: Network drop, firewall, or upstream GitHub release URL changed.\nFix:  is idempotent and supports HTTP Range resume, so re-running it is cheap:\nIf the URL changed (rare; we pin tags), you'll need a Commando upgrade: .\n---\n  on Linux ARM\nCause: Upstream  does not ship a  build. Commando skips it on purpose.\nFix: Run Walrus Sites prompts on an x8664 machine. Other Walrus operations (info, store, read) work fine on ARM.\n Sui\n \nCause: Wallet has less testnet SUI than the operation requires (typically ≥ 0.5 SUI for ).\nFix:\nIf the faucet times out, wait 5-10s and retry; the public testnet faucet is rate-limited per address.\n---\n \nCause: A pre-0.2.3-beta build hard-coded  on Linux. Upgrade.\nFix:\n---\n  runs \nCause: Pre-0.2.3-beta planner conflated build/test/publish.\nFix: Upgrade to 0.2.4-beta — the system prompt now disambiguates the verbs explicitly and the validator rejects the wrong path.\n Walrus\n \nCause:  is missing. Either bootstrap was skipped () or the auto-fetch failed.\nFix:\n---\n \nCause: Either you have no WAL coins, or your Walrus context is  but your coins are on  (or vice versa).\nFix:\nThe runtime hint that prints this error includes the same checklist.\n Site-builder\n \nCause:  is missing. Not auto-bootstrapped in 0.2.4-beta (tracked for a follow-up).\nFix:\n---\n  from \nCause: The LLM omitted the positional directory argument.\nFix: Be explicit in the prompt:\nThe 0.2.4-beta system prompt includes hardened rules for positional arguments; if you see this in 0.2.4+, file an issue with the exact prompt.\n LLM / planner\n \nCause: The model produced prose-only output and the defensive parser couldn't extract a JSON object after the configured retries.\nFix:\n1. Try a stronger model: .\n2. Re-phrase the prompt more concretely (verbs + objects, no rhetorical questions).\n3. Use the offline mock for known intents: .\n---\n \nCause: The model hallucinated a subcommand that doesn't exist in the current  CLI.\nFix: This is the validator working as intended — the planner will retry with a tighter hint. If it persists across retries:\n Safety gate\n \nCause: Your prompt matched a  rule (Layer 1) — destructive intent, key exfiltration attempt, etc.\nFix: Read the printed . If you genuinely need to do that destructive operation, run the underlying command directly — Commando doesn't execute prompts that look like system-wipe requests.\nFalse positive? File an issue with the exact prompt and the matched rule name; we'll narrow the regex.\n Diagnostics\nWhen in doubt:\nThis prints:\n- Node version and platform.\n-  path and PATH membership.\n- Per-binary status ( /  /  / ).\n- LLM provider, model, and whether the key is configured.\n-  setting.\nAttach the full  output when filing an issue.\n Still stuck?"},{"id":"/guides\\validate","title":"Validate","description":"Run cmdocs check before every commit — catch broken links, typos, and schema errors locally.","url":"/guides\\validate","content":"Validate\r\n\r\n is a fast, CI-friendly lint that catches the mistakes most likely to break your docs site. Run it locally before committing and wire it into CI so broken pages never reach .\r\n\r\n What it checks\r\n\r\n Check  Example failure \r\n------\r\n docs.json schema   ·  · unknown field \r\n Duplicate tab paths  Two tabs both resolve to  — hard error \r\n Duplicate page files  The same  file listed under two groups \r\n Navigation → MDX   \r\n MDX frontmatter   \r\n Assets   \r\n Internal links   \r\n\r\nExit code  means you're clean. Exit code  prints every failure with a file and line number, suitable for a terminal or CI log.\r\n\r\n Run it locally\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPoint at a specific source directory if your docs aren't at the repo root:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Sample output\r\n\r\nAll checks pass:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nA broken link:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Pre-commit hook (recommended)\r\n\r\nBlock bad commits before they happen. Pick whichever style fits your project.\r\n\r\n Option 1 — Native git hook (zero dependencies)\r\n\r\nCreate  (or use a tracked hooks folder via ):\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMake it executable:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Option 2 — Husky (tracked in git)\r\n\r\nIf you already use Husky, add cmdocs check to the pre-commit hook:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCommit  — every contributor who runs  gets the hook automatically.\r\n\r\n\r\n   runs the full validation in well under a second for typical docs sites. Keep it in pre-commit — it's faster than running the type-checker.\r\n\r\n\r\n CI validation\r\n\r\nAdd a validation step on every pull request so broken docs can't merge.\r\n\r\n GitHub Actions\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n GitLab CI\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Troubleshooting\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n     looks for assets under . If your favicon is at , set  (leading slash, no  prefix) in .\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    Internal links must match a page URL exactly. Tab-prefixed URLs need the tab : a page with  inside a tab with  lives at , not . Hash fragments () are stripped before validation, so those always pass.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    There is no skip flag — every failure is actionable. If you hit a false positive (e.g. a reference to an asset you know exists outside ), open an issue with the reproducer.\r\n  \r\n  \r\n    Those still work but emit a deprecation warning on every run. Migrate to  +  on tabs and groups, and object-form pages  — see Writing Content.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n Next steps"},{"id":"/guides\\writing-content","title":"Writing Content","description":"Author your docs in MDX — Markdown plus components, no imports needed.","url":"/guides\\writing-content","content":"Writing Content\r\n\r\ncmdocs uses MDX — a format that lets you use components inside Markdown. All built-in components are auto-imported, so you never need to write  statements.\r\n\r\n Frontmatter\r\n\r\nEvery page starts with a YAML frontmatter block at the top of the file:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  SEO tips\r\n  - Keep  under 160 characters — longer descriptions get truncated in search results.\r\n  - Use a concrete verb in the  (e.g. \"Install the CLI\" not just \"Installation\") so search snippets read well.\r\n  - Add a global  in  to set the default social preview image; override per-page later when you add one.\r\n\r\n\r\n Markdown basics\r\n\r\nAll standard Markdown features work as you'd expect.\r\n\r\n Text formatting\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Links\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nInternal links use absolute paths starting from the site root.\r\n\r\n Lists\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Blockquotes\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Code blocks\r\n\r\nUse fenced code blocks with a language identifier for syntax highlighting:\r\n\r\ntypescript\r\nfunction greet(name: string): string !\r\n\r\nYou can also add a  to the block:\r\n\r\nts title=\"src/greet.ts\"\r\nexport const greet = (name: string) = ;\r\npublic/public/logo/light.svg/logo/light.svgpublic/images/docs.jsonpagesfile.mdxpathlabelguides/setup.mdx/documentation/guides/setupdocumentationpathDeploy guidecmdocs checkfull: truepublic/public/images/hero.png/images/hero.png`. SVG is preferred for logos and diagrams (sharper on retina, smaller payload).\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n Next"},{"id":"/reference\\cli","title":"CLI Reference","description":"Every cmdo subcommand and flag in v0.2.4-beta.","url":"/reference\\cli","content":"CLI Reference\n is a Commander-based CLI. The default action takes a free-text prompt; the rest are reserved subcommand names.\n Synopsis\n Global options\n Option  Description \n------\n ,   Print the installed version (e.g. ). \n ,   Print help. \n Subcommands\n \nInteractively configure the LLM provider, API key, and model.\nPrompts:\n1. Provider —  or .\n2. API key — pasted at the prompt; stored in .\n3. Model — picked from a curated dropdown (or accept the default).\nRe-run any time to switch providers or models. Env vars (, , , ) override the stored config when present.\n \nPrint environment status and verify installed binaries. Read-only — does not download or modify anything.\nOutput includes Node version, platform, install root, PATH membership, per-binary status, and LLM provider configuration. See Troubleshooting for what to do when checks fail.\nExit code:  if all checks pass,  otherwise.\n \nDownload binaries, patch PATH, bootstrap external CLI configs, and (re)generate skills. Idempotent — safe to re-run.\nUse this after a partial install (network drop), after upgrading the package, or to recover from a stale state. To force a full re-download, delete  first.\n \nRegenerate  from the currently installed binaries'  output.\nRun this after any of the upstream binaries change versions — the LLM planner is constrained to the contract in , so a stale contract means stale plans.\n \nThe default action. Anything that isn't a known subcommand is treated as a natural-language prompt.\n Routing flags\nIf multiple are passed, the first one wins.\n Flag  Forces \n------\n   Plan against the  binary skill section only. \n   Plan against the  binary skill section only. \n   Plan against the  binary skill section only. \nWhen no flag is passed, the router infers the target from prompt keywords. Always pass the explicit flag in scripts and demos for predictability.\n Exit codes\n Code  Meaning \n------\n   Plan succeeded, executed, and exited 0. \n   Generic failure (LLM error, validation failure, spawn failure, exec non-zero). \n   Underlying binary's exit code is propagated. \n Examples\n Wallet\n Move\n Walrus\n Walrus Sites\n Where the binary lives\n OS  Path \n------\n Windows   (npm global bin) →  for upstream binaries \n Linux / macOS   →  for upstream binaries \n Related"},{"id":"/reference\\env-vars","title":"Environment Variables","description":"Every CMDO_*, OPENAI_*, OPENROUTER_* variable Commando reads, with defaults.","url":"/reference\\env-vars","content":"Environment Variables\nAll variables are read at process start. There is no live reload — change the env, then re-run .\n Installer\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Any non-empty value other than  /  skips the postinstall download. Use  later. \n     Parallel downloads during bootstrap. Lower on flaky networks. \n     Per-chunk idle timeout in milliseconds. Increase for slow links. \n     Attempts per file before giving up. \n Optional R2 manifest mirror (Windows only)\nThe R2 path is off by default. Set both vars to enable. When either is missing, the install falls back to GitHub-direct.\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Full URL to the manifest JSON in R2 (or any compatible mirror). \n   unset  Bearer/header token the worker accepts. \n  No secret is shipped inside the npm tarball — both halves must come from the operator's environment. See Installation for the security rationale.\n LLM provider\nEnv vars override the values stored by  in .\n OpenAI\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Required if provider is OpenAI and no config file exists. \n     Override the model. Any string accepted by the OpenAI API. \n OpenRouter\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n   unset  Required if provider is OpenRouter and no config file exists. \n     Override the model. Any string accepted by OpenRouter. \n Planner\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n     Set to  to bypass the LLM and use the deterministic regex-based mock planner. Useful for offline demos and CI. \n Logging\n Variable  Default  Purpose \n---------\n     One of , , , .  adds raw LLM input/output and validator decisions. \n   unset  Standard env: any non-empty value disables ANSI colors. \n Examples\n CI build that defers the binary download\n Air-gapped install pulling from a private R2 mirror\n Prefer env-only LLM setup (no )\n Offline hackathon demo\n Related"}]}